Géza von Cziffra was a film director and screenwriter active in Hungary and Germany from the 1930s onwards, known for directing films such as "Tanzende Sterne" (1952) and "Kriminaltango" (1960), as well as the 1949 film "Dangerous Guests." He worked primarily in the European film industry, with a focus on revue and comedy films, and was also involved in screenwriting. His career spanned several decades, and he directed films in both German and Austrian cinema.

Henry Selick is an American stop-motion director, producer, and writer, best known for directing "The Nightmare Before Christmas" (1993), "James and the Giant Peach" (1996), and "Coraline" (2009). He has worked extensively in the field of stop-motion animation, a niche but highly specialized area of filmmaking. Selick has collaborated with Tim Burton and founded Skellington Productions, a joint venture with Burton that specialized in stop-motion animation. His work has been recognized for its artistic and technical innovation in the animation industry.

Comparing the scope of their professions, Géza von Cziffra had a broader range of work in terms of film genres and formats, including live-action films, revue films, and comedies, and he was active in multiple European countries. Henry Selick, while highly influential in the field of stop-motion animation, has focused more narrowly on this specific medium. Therefore, Géza von Cziffra had a wider scope of profession in terms of the variety of film types and international film industry involvement. 

